1G-wIL4SUEeLzHsY4saPMrgXL7Cs3XgMBnocILYfKU2nT7Mnn7V85nEa4fcbvttKr3GVJjID8Gc=
A3m7YD3XJ2pPPwS_2lkwD915HfU1sUI-4Z-jcgvb4ndKfZJPdHVxdI9g4K4oogC9nF4ZQ ). Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s Twitter, though, has been haphazard and blistering in its pace=
. What ought to concern the company about Threads, though, is the possibili=
ty that all of the upheaval =E2=80=94 which effectively sacrifices the nich=
e Twitter had carved out amongst text nerds that dominate industries like m=
edia =E2=80=94 will not actually result in the user growth Musk is hoping f=
or, because Threads got there first.

Indeed, this map is the key to understanding why it is that Threads looks l=
ike Twitter, but is in fact a very different product: Threads is solidly pl=
anted in the upper right. When you log onto the app for the first time, you=
r feed is populated by the algorithm; there is some context given by whom y=
ou follow on Instagram, but Meta seems aware that accounts you might want t=
o look at may be different than accounts you want to hear from, and is thus=
 filling the feeds with what it thinks you might find interesting. That is =
how it can provide an at-least-somewhat-compelling first-run experience to =
100 million people in five days ( https://www.threads.net/t/CuhOXGmr74R/?ig=
shid=3DMTc4MmM1YmI2Ng%3D%3D ).

Twitter, on the other hand, faces the burden of millions having tried the s=
ervice in past iterations and quickly deciding it wasn=E2=80=99t for them; =
even if the algorithm were effective, it may already be too late to gain ne=
w users, even as you sacrifice what the service=E2=80=99s existing users pr=
eferred.

The Threads Experiment
----------------------

This leads to the biggest open question about Threads=E2=80=99 long-term pr=
ospects, and, by extension, Twitter=E2=80=99s: did those millions of abando=
ned Twitter users give up because text-based social networking just wasn=E2=
=80=99t that interesting to them, or because Twitter made it too hard to ge=
t started? I=E2=80=99ve made the case ( https://stratechery.com/2021/twitte=
r-has-a-new-ceo-what-about-a-new-business-model/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJ=
SUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.e=
yJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1Ay=
WURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIxL3R=
3aXR0ZXItaGFzLWEtbmV3LWNlby13aGF0LWFib3V0LWEtbmV3LWJ1c2luZXNzLW1vZGVsLyJdfS=
wiZXhwIjoxNjkxNjY5MzUwLCJpYXQiOjE2ODkwNzczNTAsImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc=
3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGljbGU6cmVhZCBhc3Nl=
dDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFd=
KZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.DXIF6zng_MXDhUbejq_ORTdHtCYSGB78xr7y_NGWI=
I_mDedG9g3iCgzuG1fVA0OoWfINxh8i0Mo5p8ABaLgRyCNBfJ5jF72Eb79HkW7sbAjEis6lo4gT=
B4O62_tyPCkHEO2iiCufktbbRzwrSFW3sRLO-9foAddDpCIhBsbWsNM9lZJ5oxUbKN-v8tfY0-_=
mC4zOLaWKQlQRtiNZkHp7_4a6MCnxsFptK_yWZYKwHpGg5-Z_Ym-oOnv8-laOZib1JVLTYNGEgH=
2p32enQ5CsgbObaSLQ_sH7VB3i4wMlYt8g3JIfhkT_tqUGDOiahyZ8o9FdmyAZEUZWyfXe_tu4z=
w ) that it=E2=80=99s the former, which means that Threads is a grand exper=
iment as to the validity of that thesis. If those 100 million users stay en=
gaged (and if that number continues to grow), then the people chalking up T=
witter=E2=80=99s inability to grow or monetize effectively to the company=
=E2=80=99s inability to execute are correct.

At the same time, as Wei notes, Musk=E2=80=99s tenure has highlighted the p=
roblems with doing too much: what if Twitter succeeded to the extent it did=
 not despite management=E2=80=99s seeming ineffectiveness, but because of i=
t?

I=E2=80=99ve written before in Status as a Service ( https://www.eugenewei.=
com/blog/2019/2/19/status-as-a-service ) or The Network=E2=80=99s the Thing=
 ( https://www.eugenewei.com/blog/2015/9/1/when-the-network-is-mature ) abo=
ut how Twitter hit upon some narrow product-market fit despite itself. It h=
as never seemed to understand why it worked for some people or what it want=
ed to be, and how those two were related, if at all. But in a twist of fate=
 that is often more of a factor in finding product-market fit than most lik=
e to admit, Twitter=E2=80=99s indecisiveness protected it from itself. Soci=
al alchemy at some scale can be a mysterious thing. When you=E2=80=99re unc=
ertain which knot is securing your body to the face of a mountain, it=E2=80=
=99s best not to start undoing any of them willy-nilly. Especially if, as I=
 think was the case for Twitter, the knots were tied by someone else (in th=
is case, the users of Twitter themselves).

Many of those knots are tied to that lower left quadrant: a predominantly t=
ime-based feed makes sense if a service is predominantly about =E2=80=9CWha=
t is happening?=E2=80=9D, to use Twitter=E2=80=99s long-time prompt; a grap=
h based on who you choose to follow doesn=E2=80=99t just show what you want=
 to see, it also controls what you don=E2=80=99t (Wei notes that this is a =
particularly hard problem for algorithmically generated feeds). Both qualit=
ies seem particularly pertinent for a medium (text) that is information den=
se and favored by people interested in harvesting information, a very diffe=
rent goal than looking to pass the time with an entertaining video or ten.

It follows, then, that Twitter=E2=80=99s best defense against Threads may b=
e to retreat to that lower left corner: focus on what is happening now, fro=
m people you chose to follow. The problem, though, is that while this might=
 win the battle against Threads, it means that Musk will have lost the war =
when it comes to ever making a return on his $44 billion. In truth, though,=
 that war is already lost: Musk=E2=80=99s lurch for the upper right was pro=
bably the best path to reigniting user growth, but if that is the corner th=
at matters then Threads will win.

Thread=E2=80=99s Chronological Timeline
-------------------------------

The other question is if Threads will come for Twitter=E2=80=99s place on t=
he map; Head of Instagram Adam Mosseri says that a chronological timeline i=
s coming:

Adam Mosseri promising a chronological timeline ( https://www.threads.net/t=
/CuYvSTItD5L/?igshid=3DMTc4MmM1YmI2Ng%3D%3D )

Placing this option in the context of Facebook and Instagram actually sugge=
sts that this feature won=E2=80=99t matter very much; both services make it=
 hard to find, and revert back to the default algorithmic feed, and for goo=
d reason: users may say they want a chronological feed, but their revealed =
preference is the opposite. Instagram founders Kevin Systrom and Mike Krieg=
er, who initially opposed algorithmic ranking in Instagram, told me in a St=
ratechery Interview ( https://stratechery.com/2023/an-interview-with-kevin-=
systrom-and-mike-krieger-about-artifact/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiI=
sImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiO=
iJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQ=
V00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LmNvbS8yMDIzL2FuLWludGV=
ydmlldy13aXRoLWtldmluLXN5c3Ryb20tYW5kLW1pa2Uta3JpZWdlci1hYm91dC1hcnRpZmFjdC=
8jcmFua2luZyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNjkxNjY5MzUwLCJpYXQiOjE2ODkwNzczNTAsImlzcyI6Imh0d=
HBzOi8vYXBpLnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZS9vYXV0aCIsInNjb3BlIjoiZmVlZDpyZWFkIGFydGlj=
bGU6cmVhZCBhc3NldDpyZWFkIGNhdGVnb3J5OnJlYWQgZW50aXRsZW1lbnRzIiwic3ViIjoiUnN=
ldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.RAtC5goaTVW0RNHppkYwP4ig-=
twxOHWrCR0Ww5kjyGGqBiJF8ODBHVYlEH80hFaZUTOXpiIzBSOqGZPukzHvL9tjrBGhJyasFqd6=
YLMG5LFjAsBJD-dS8EJvqmJUQs3L9HbpmF-hjTekEA31FqWNnWfUWiGTnxVFj5DmTceCohQQKOx=
7LW2PxNIM7-QRPouUTPC8cq-BvXCNCvcsbA5mmuHGzt8zEAwQocoTbouumkiklMP3H-QgGs_jlA=
9SUfhM93sdCjdi8SPImwVsC6nyOfKV8fRdQqQwzGOD5C30LnGlwYI-L23sf7pyDbkyJ20gVuIZi=
qtIiR1XpGfo6MBWWA#ranking ) :

*Kevin Systrom:* I remember thinking when the team was like, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=
=80=99re thinking of using machine learning to sort the Explore page,=E2=80=
=9D I=E2=80=99m not even sure what they call it now, but basically the Expl=
ore page and I remember saying, =E2=80=9CIt just feels like that=E2=80=99s =
a bunch of hocus-pocus that won=E2=80=99t work. Or maybe it=E2=80=99ll work=
 but you won=E2=80=99t really understand what it=E2=80=99s doing and you wo=
n=E2=80=99t fully understand the implications of it, so we should probably =
just keep it very simple.=E2=80=9D I was so wrong and I only remember it be=
cause I was so wrong, but you asked about feed, Mike would probably give yo=
u his anecdote about feed. But on the Explore page I was very anti and then=
 I think I became pro only once I saw what it could do. Not in terms of jus=
t usage metrics, but just the quality of what people were served compared t=
o some of our heuristics before=E2=80=A6

*Mike Krieger:* I=E2=80=99ll share a funny anecdote about the Explore exper=
iment. Facebook has all these internal A/B testing tooling and we hooked in=
to it and we ran our first machine learning on the Explore experiment and w=
e filed a bug report and I=E2=80=99m like, =E2=80=9CHey, your tool isn=E2=
=80=99t working, that=E2=80=99s not reporting results here.=E2=80=9D And th=
ey said, =E2=80=9CNo, the results are just so strong that they=E2=80=99re l=
iterally off the charts. The little bars that show it literally is over 200=
%, you just should ship this yesterday.=E2=80=9D The data looked really goo=
d.

That noted, observe Mosseri=E2=80=99s stated goal for the app, as articulat=
ed to Alex Heath of The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2023/7/5/23784870/=
instagram-threads-adam-mosseri-interview-twitter-competitor ) :

I think success will be creating a vibrant community, particularly of creat=
ors, because I do think this sort of public space is really, even more than=
 most other types of social networks, a place where a small number of peopl=
e produce most of the content that most everyone consumes. So I think it=E2=
=80=99s really about creators more than it is about average folks who I thi=
nk are much more there just to be entertained. I think [we want] a vibrant =
community of creators that=E2=80=99s really culturally relevant. It would b=
e great if it gets really, really big, but I=E2=80=99m actually more intere=
sted in if it becomes culturally relevant and if it gets hundreds of millio=
ns of users. But we=E2=80=99ll see how it goes over the next couple of mont=
hs or probably a couple of years.

=E2=80=9CCulturally relevant=E2=80=9D is the one game that Twitter has won,=
 far more than Facebook, and arguably more than Instagram: Twitter drives n=
ational and international media coverage, from TV to newspapers, to an exte=
nt that drastically exceeds its monetization potential. Meta, meanwhile, ha=
s been content to provide social networking for the silent majority, making=
 tons of money along the way. The best way to do that with text =E2=80=94 i=
f it is even possible =E2=80=94 would be to stay in that upper right corner=
; cultural relevancy, though, is still in the bottom left, even if there ar=
en=E2=80=99t nearly as many users, or money.

And, it must be noted, Twitter is vulnerable in its home territory; I=E2=80=
=99ve long argued that the importance of convenience in terms of app succes=
s is underrated (see Threads starting with your Instagram sign-in and netwo=
rk), but its hard to think of anything that might motivate users to make a =
change more than resolving cognitive dissonance. There is a sizable segment=
 of that culturally relevant audience Mosseri wants to capture who are oppo=
sed to Musk, and yet can=E2=80=99t give up Twitter; I suspect that much of =
the outpouring of glee over Threads=E2=80=99 early success is from this coh=
ort that wants nothing more than non-Musk Twitter.

Ultimately, though, I think they may be disappointed: Meta is about algorit=
hms and scale, and I would bet that Threads will leave real time reactions,=
 news, and pitched battles to Twitter; Musk=E2=80=99s most important decisi=
on may be accepting that that is enough, because it=E2=80=99s all he=E2=80=
=99s going to get.

